<TITLE>Many surprises await in tension-filled 'Split'</TITLE>


<TEXT>
If I had to <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">sum</EVENT> up M. Night Shyamalans Split in one sentence, I would <EVENT eid="e2" class="REPORTING">say</EVENT> it has personality. Lots of personality. 
 
The psychological thriller is about Casey, Claire and Marcia (Anya Taylor-Joy, Haley Lu Richardson and Jessica Sula), three high school girls who are <EVENT eid="e3" class="STATE">kidnapped</EVENT>. Their assailant is Kevin Crumb, a man with dissociative identity disorder, <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">resulting</EVENT> in 23 separate identities in one body. 
 
James McAvoy, who plays Kevin and Dennis, Patricia and the rest of Kevins alters shows off his extensive acting abilities as he plays multiple characters mostly through voice and body language alone. The switches in demeanor are almost reminiscent of a theater-character exercise, they are so quickly and drastically <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">portrayed</EVENT>. 
 
The dissociative personality disorder <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">isnt</EVENT> the twist of Split, though; <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">revealed</EVENT> from the start, it is not one of the many surprises that await. 
 
Kevins <EVENT eid="e8" class="REPORTING">therapist</EVENT> Dr. Fletcher (Betty Buckley) sprinkles exposition by the handful throughout the movie, but also provides another layer of character that the film sorely <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">needed</EVENT>. Out of the three kidnapped girls. Casey is the most <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">fleshed</EVENT> out, her backstory being <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">revealed</EVENT> through tasteful flashbacks. 
 
