For the first half of the movie, tension was evenly balanced, the creeping confusion of the unknown perfectly <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">interspersed</EVENT> with laughable moments. The second half was where it <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">fell</EVENT> flat. Split <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">felt</EVENT> choppy and hurriedly <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">borrowed</EVENT> from common horror movies. 
 
The movie is rated PG-13, yet <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">presented</EVENT> its main actresses unnecessarily half-dressed for a good <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">portion</EVENT> of the feature. I had high hopes for great character development, but whether it was too tight of a script or just bad writing, there was simply no room for growth. 
 
Yet the near absence of gore was a refreshing breath of air in the otherwise blood-soaked horror industry. An appropriately balanced score <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">added</EVENT> to the atmosphere of Split, and good cinematography <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">brought</EVENT> the tone of the movie to a suspenseful simmer. 
 
Overall, I would <EVENT eid="e21" class="REPORTING">say</EVENT> that Split is a film best for <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">watching</EVENT> at home with friends and cheap pizza. The movie wasnt bad by any means, but as I <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">watched</EVENT> the end credits <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">roll</EVENT>, I <EVENT eid="e25" class="I_STATE">felt</EVENT> unsatisfied. 
 
The only explanation I can think of is that the hype surrounding Split was just too great, and I had mistakenly <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">expected</EVENT> more from the film. 
 
